english:
  title: Preface to the Diagram of the Orthodox and Unorthodox
  author: Lee Sun-ji
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the tenth month of the first year of Tianshun, on an auspicious day, the Emperor summoned me to his private chamber and showed me the Imperial Treatise on the Diagram of the Orthodox and Unorthodox, together with its supplementary sections. He spoke to me thus:

    "In my days before ascending the throne, when treacherous forces spread their poison and the necessity of restoring order could not be denied, I, burning with resolve and spurred by ambition, composed these writings almost by chance. Yet now reviewing them, they seem to contain genuine principle. The supplementary sections were written at another time and, though rough in places, contain within them the Way of Yin-Yang and the Orthodox and Unorthodox. They may serve as a stepping stone to investigating things and extending knowledge, and as a warning to those who would apply no effort to understanding. However, in these pages the methods of divining fate are merely cited but not fully developed. You, Lee Sun-ji, together with Choi Ho-won, should gather the various texts on fate-divining, eliminate what is redundant, extract what is essential, and compose illustrative examples so that beginning students may easily comprehend them."

    Upon withdrawing, we recorded the scope of the Five Phases, the numerical patterns of the Three Heavens, and the foundational principles of the various methods of stars, celestial animals, and Purple Subtlety. Wherever beginning students might find cause for doubt, we composed illustrative examples for each point and submitted them. The Emperor, by his sage judgment, refined and completed them, naming the work the Supplementary Compendium of the Diagram of the Orthodox and Unorthodox, which he placed between the main diagram and its outer sections, commanding me to write this account of its origins.

    I, Lee Sun-ji, humbly reflect that when the Great Ultimate first divided, there must necessarily have been this principle. Where principle exists, form exists. Where form exists, number exists. Where number exists, it is contained within the Five Phases. What the Five Phases embody is nothing but the odd and even of Yin and Yang.

    The sun and moon, the stars and planets—these are Heaven's patterns wherein both Yin and Yang are present. Mountains and rivers, grasses and trees—these are Earth's patterns wherein both Yin and Yang are present. Poetry, History, Ritual, and Music—these are humanity's patterns wherein both Yin and Yang are present. Spring, summer, autumn, winter—these are the Yin and Yang of one year. Dawn, dusk, day, night—these are the Yin and Yang of one day. Initial, correct, quarter, and minute—these are the Yin and Yang of one hour. Is not movement and stillness, speech and silence, Yin and Yang? Are not inhalation and exhalation, bending and extending, Yin and Yang? Even the clarity and turbidity, the highness and lowness of sound; the left and right, the horizontal and vertical of written characters—none of these escape being Yin and Yang.

    The Orthodox and Unorthodox are themselves Yin and Yang. Within Yin dwells Yang; within Yang dwells Yin. Within the Unorthodox dwells the Orthodox; within the Orthodox dwells the Unorthodox. They generate and perfect one another in endless transformation. We do not call this the Diagram of Yin-Yang but rather the Diagram of the Orthodox and Unorthodox because military strategy never departs from the Orthodox and Unorthodox. Thus at this time the Emperor's primary intent was to suppress disorder and restore righteousness, and adopting the analogy of the game of go, he gave it this name—not as mere entertainment, but as serious principle.

    The essential aim is to illuminate for people the principle of how Yin and Yang wax and wane, to probe the source of generation and completion, death and severance, to understand the causes of calamity and auspiciousness, misfortune and blessing, to comprehend the Way of victory and defeat, fortune and misfortune, and through vigilance and reverence to return all things to the Center and the Correct. Should one truly grasp this, then those who study diagrams and books will penetrate the principles and numbers; those who engage in battle will employ the Orthodox and Unorthodox; those who know their fate will be content with their station; those who encounter calamity will increase their vigilance; and nowhere will they fail to exhaust the fullness of application.

    Thus this book, in its creation, can reveal on the grand scale the transformations of Heaven and Earth, and on the small scale the flourishing and withering of plants and trees, the length and brevity of human life, the order or disorder of family affairs, the constancy and variation of military strategy, the rightness and wrongness of counsel and planning. How could anything escape the bounds of these patterns?

    Some object: "Is it not burdensome and confusing to include fate-divining alongside these teachings? The ancient sages said: 'Of what use is a hairpin where there is no hair? What need is there for walls in a cave or nest? The soldiers buried at Changping did not all violate the Three Inauspicious Positions; those related near Nanyang need not all accord with the Six Harmonious Positions. To praise people's fates to delight their hearts, to adjust predictions of fortune and misfortune to regulate talents—such mockery shows that fate-divining is unworthy of credence.'"

    But this is not so. For even the smallest creatures—grasses, trees, and animals—each possess an innate fate. How much more so humanity, the finest of all creatures, which surely possesses fates of nobility or baseness, longevity or early death? Since the Han dynasty, books on fate have flourished in the world. Those of penetrating understanding and keen intelligence have always used them to divine the past and discern the future, and they accord with the subtle workings of cosmic transformation. Therefore one cannot dismiss this matter with mere mockery. Moreover, the books on fate-divining are truly rooted in the foundations of Yin-Yang, the Five Phases, and the principles and numbers, and they are complementary to this diagram. This is why the Emperor commanded their inclusion and why we composed this supplementary compendium in accordance with his intention.

    Alas! The Book of Changes of Fu-xi, King Wen, the Duke of Zhou, and Confucius—the Four Sages—becomes all the more illuminated through this diagram. The writings of the Duke of Jiang, Sun Wu, and Wu Qi become all the more manifest. Yet what most reveals the Emperor's brilliance is his profound mastery of the principles of Nature and his subtle understanding of military formations. His wisdom in creating patterns of understanding is supreme and without limit.
